General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The recovered material or the products or by-products of operations that
2 process recovered material shall not be discharged, deposited, injected,
3 dumped, spilled, leaked, or placed into or upon any land or water so that the
4 products or by-products or any constituent thereof may enter other lands or be
5 emitted into the air or discharged into any waters including groundwaters, or
6 otherwise enter the environment or pose a threat to public health and safety.
7 Facilities that process recovered material shall be operated in a manner to
8 ensure compliance with this subdivision.
9 (3) The recovered material shall not be a hazardous waste or have been recovered
10 from a hazardous waste.
11 (4) The recovered material shall not contain significant concentrations of foreign
12 constituents that render it unserviceable or inadequate for sale, or its intended
13 use or reuse.
14 (d) Beneficial Use Determination. – For the purposes of preservation of landfill capacity,
15 economic development, energy savings, and reduction of greenhouse emissions, the Department
16 may determine whether nonhazardous solid waste may be used or reused for a particular site or
17 application as an alternative to disposal at a permitted solid waste management facility as set
18 forth in this subsection.
19 (1) A person seeking a beneficial use determination shall submit an application to
20 the Department. The Department, after a review of an application submitted
21 under this subsection, may take any of the following actions:
22 a. Authorize management of a specified type of nonhazardous solid
23 waste at a site other than a permitted solid waste management facility.
24 b. Issue a beneficial use determination with appropriate conditions for
25 use of specific types of solid waste in construction, land application,
26 or other projects and applications.
27 (2) An applicant for a determination under this subsection shall submit
28 information on forms prescribed by the Department and any additional
29 information required by the Department necessary for a determination under
30 this subsection. In its review of the application and additional information, the
31 Department shall also consider internal research or information submitted by
32 any person or entity concerning the potential hazard to public health or the
33 environment of any type of solid waste.
34 (3) The Department may require submittal of a demonstration that the solid waste
35 is being managed in a manner to protect public health or the environment and
36 may include any of the following as a part of an authorization under
37 subdivision (1) of this subsection:
38 a. Requirements for periodic testing of solid wastes.
39 b. Conditions to ensure that the products or by-products of a material
40 recovered or diverted for beneficial use shall not be discharged,
41 deposited, injected, dumped, spilled, leaked, or placed into or upon
42 any land or water so that the products or by-products or any
43 constituents thereof may enter other lands or be emitted into the air, or
44 discharged into any waters, including groundwaters, or otherwise enter
45 the environment or pose a threat to public health and safety.
46 (4) Approvals granted under this subsection are valid for no longer than five
47 years. Requests for renewal shall be made at least 60 days in advance of the
48 expiration date of the approval.
49 (5) The applicant for a determination under this subsection shall submit to the
50 Department on an annual basis a report detailing the usage of material under
